ROOT CAUSE: program.cpp:3-5. The function 'fib' is implemented as a naive recursive function without a base case (e.g., if n <= 1 return n). This causes infinite recursion, which exhausts the stack memory, resulting in a stack-overflow crash.

LOCAL FIX: Add a base case to the 'fib' function:
int fib(int n) {
  if (n <= 1) return n;
  return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
}

GLOBAL FIX: For recursive algorithms, always enforce base case validation or use iterative approaches (dynamic programming/memoization) to avoid stack overflow and exponential time complexity. In production code, consider using tail-call optimization or iterative loops for performance-critical or deep recursion scenarios.

